{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1462"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1462"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.31,0.26,0.26,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99994"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1462"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34319"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99994"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a six hour history of colicky abdominal pain associated with distension. The pain is generalised across the lower abdomen. There has been no trauma. Her medical history includes a mechanical mitral valve replacement, for which she takes warfarin. On examination, the abdomen is tender, distended and without features of peritonism. Increased, tinkling bowel sounds can be heard. There is a firm and non-reducible swelling in the right groin region. A CT scan is performed and one of the sagittal views is shown (mid-point of the inguinal canal) (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is shown on the scan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rectus sheath haematoma","Indirect inguinal hernia","Femoral hernia","Direct inguinal hernia","Saphena varix"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sagittal view of the CT scan series shows an \u003Cstrong\u003Eindirect inguinal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E, where abdominal contents (typically bowel) pass through the inguinal ring and into the inguinal canal - shown by the arrow (Image). The patient is experiencing abdominal pain and the hernia is irreducible, which is concerning for strangulation (although the swelling is not tender at this stage) and requires immediate surgical input.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral hernias\u003C/strong\u003E are more common in women and of high risk of strangulation. However, these travel through the femoral ring. \u003Cstrong\u003EDirect inguinal hernias\u003C/strong\u003E occur medial to the deep ring, where the aponeurosis of the abdominal wall is most weak.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient is on warfarin, a \u003Cstrong\u003Erectus sheath haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable differential for an abdominal mass with pain. Other findings may include a history of trauma, haemodynamic instability and abdominal bruising. These haematomas are typically deep to the rectus abdominis muscle and do not extend into the groin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esaphena varix\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to dilation of of the saphenous vein at the saphenofemoral junction. This is may result in a palpable groin mass and will typically be associated with varicose veins elsewhere in the limb. These swellings are soft.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EIn this particular case it could be argued that the CT scan was unnecessary as the diagnosis of small bowel obstruction secondary to an incarcerated inguinal hernia should have been very clinically evident.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Indirect inguinal hernias pass through the inguinal ring"],"references":["Turner R. A general practitioner primer on groin hernias. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2018;47(8):530-533. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/august/general-practitioner-primer-on-groin-hernias"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20025"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20026"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20025"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f4f7a4f8-f1dc-4f62-871c-74ee8f4c345a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f4f7a4f8-f1dc-4f62-871c-74ee8f4c345a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":751,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20026"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ded79be8-576e-4cee-aee3-26c29814a3c1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ded79be8-576e-4cee-aee3-26c29814a3c1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":751,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T18:54:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T18:54:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1462"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":